# Next.js, TypeScript & React Guidelines

## Project Configuration

- Next.js 16 with App Router architecture
- TypeScript with strict mode enabled (see [tsconfig.json](mdc:dapp/tsconfig.json))
- React 19 with React Server Components
- Tailwind CSS 4 for styling
- Path aliases: `@/*` maps to `dapp/*`

## Code Standards

- Use TypeScript strict mode - always type your variables and function parameters
- Prefer functional components with hooks
- Use React Server Components by default (no 'use client' unless needed)
- Add 'use client' directive only when using browser APIs, hooks, or event handlers

## File Structure

- Pages/components in `app/` directory following Next.js App Router conventions
- Use `page.tsx` for route pages
- Use `layout.tsx` for shared layouts
- Static assets in `public/` directory

## Styling Guidelines

- Use Tailwind CSS utility classes
- Support dark mode with `dark:` prefix
- Follow responsive design patterns: mobile-first approach
- Use semantic HTML elements

## TypeScript Best Practices

- Define interfaces/types for props and data structures
- Avoid `any` type - use `unknown` if type is truly unknown
- Use type inference where appropriate
- Export types/interfaces when reused

## Component Patterns

```typescript
// Server Component (default)
export default function Component() {
  return <div>Content</div>;
}

// Client Component (when needed)
("use client");
import { useState } from "react";
export default function InteractiveComponent() {
  const [state, setState] = useState(0);
  return <button onClick={() => setState(state + 1)}>{state}</button>;
}
```

## Web3 Integration (Future)

- When integrating Web3, use libraries like ethers.js, viem, or wagmi
- Always handle wallet connection errors gracefully
- Show loading states during blockchain transactions
- Display transaction status and confirmations
